        <body>
            <p>This is a very comprehensive survey of the existing research on the question of identity in the mutual perceptions of Turks and Europeans over a long period of history. The review is divided into four periods, the first starting with the final century of the Ottoman Empire and the last ending with the Turkey-EU refugee deal in 2016. With this comprehensive approach, the authors hope to fill a lacunae in the literature: there are few studies of the mutual representation between these two actors over the 
                <italic>long dur&#x00e9;e</italic>. They express the hope that their review can provide the basis for an "evolutionary analysis of mutual identity representations between the two sides over more than a two-hundred-year period." (p. 3)</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The authors structure the examination of the literature in each period by first presenting a historical context, after which they turn to European representations of the Ottoman Empire, and then to Ottoman representations of Europe. They conclude the examination of each period by discussing four focal issues: nationalism, civilization, status in international society, and state-citizen relations. These four issues are no doubt interesting and important, and the discussion of them is informative, but there is no prior discussion that explains the theoretical or practical significance of these issues, or why these and not others were chosen. A slightly stronger theoretical framework for the review could have enhanced the coherence of the review.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The review is long and very rich in information. It is a gold mine for anyone interested in a birds-eye view of the mutual representation of identity and otherness between Ottomans/Turks and (non-Turkish) Europeans. This review should be a natural starting point for students and scholars writing on this topic in the future, and the concluding identification of eight major gaps in the literature should point the way to future research. The review is easily accessible and written in a straight forward manner by scholars who clearly know the topic. The focus on the mutuality of representations is one of the strong points of the study, as much of the literature (generally speaking) has tended to focus on European representations of Turkey and Turks. The periodization is reasonable and there were many revelations for me when reading.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> On the critical side, the authors could have discussed the Turkey-Europe dichotomy that they assume in a more reflective manner. Does the use of this dichotomy reify the construct that Turkey is not part of/partly Europe? The review is, as has been noted above, short on theory. A fuller theoretical discussion of in particular the four focal issues could have been useful. The reading of the research is generally very good, but the ambition to cover a vast topic means that the readings of the literature is at times somewhat shallow. There are minor but consistent grammatical errors (in particular when it comes to definite/indefinite articles) that marginally detract from the presentation.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> When it comes to limitations, it is not clear why the project begins with the French Revolution and not sooner. There were, of course, interactions between the Ottoman Empire and Christian kingdoms in Europe prior to that date. The review could have benefited from a motivation for this choice of limitation. Having said that, the period covered is already vast and extending it further could have made it unwieldy. Another limitation is that only works in two languages--English and Turkish--are included. Europe is of course much bigger than just the UK and while English has become the 
                <italic>lingua franca</italic> of academia, the exclusion of sources in eg: German and French might have had consequences for the findings. On the other hand, just including Turkish sources is a significant improvement of the existing scholarship. A recommendation for future scholarship that wants to build on this review would be to add sources in other languages.</p>
