            <p>
                <bold>INTRODUCTION</bold>
            </p>
            <p> Aiming to analyse a period of more than 200 years is a challenging but original attempt to unveil the bigger picture of Turkish-European relations within the specific dimension of identity. The research sample of this article is based on three periods, all of which are important for a better understanding of T&#x00fc;rkiye's relations with Europe. The periods do not have similar characteristics. The first period is by far the longest. It contains so many controversial and historical events that even historians find it difficult to understand. The second and third periods are more manageable, although the literature on these years is probably more time-consuming. The article is interested in four focal points that are useful to explain the historical and contemporary aspects of T&#x00fc;rkiye-EU relations within the framework of the notion of "identity".</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> This article is instructive. The bibliography gathered in the research includes 313 works, which makes the study powerful and unique in its field. The article not only presents the overall picture in the literature, but also presents important but little known details that help to analyse what the article focuses on. For example, Kaiser Wilhelm's trip to Istanbul and Jerusalem and his spiritual experience on that trip make the article more interesting to read. Another stimulating and instructive detail is the establishment of the "Turkish National Council of the European Movement" and the "European Youth Campaign" and the contribution of the two leading political parties, the CHP and the DP, to them.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> One of the original features of this study is its comprehensiveness. The literature review does not only include research from political science, international relations, sociology or media studies. Some examples presented in the article originate from representations of T&#x00fc;rkiye's European or non-European identity in arts and literature. Even a section focuses on the history of education in T&#x00fc;rkiye, discussing textbooks from the Republican period. Another originality of this work is the scope of the literature. Most studies on T&#x00fc;rkiye-EU relations use data from the most powerful EU countries, such as Germany, France and the UK (before Brexit), and sometimes Italy and T&#x00fc;rkiye's neighbour Greece. However, this study also refers to the research related to the reverberations of T&#x00fc;rkiye's European identity in less popular European countries in T&#x00fc;rkiye-EU relations such as Norway, Czech Republic, Slovakia, Romania and Bulgaria.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <bold>SOME CRITIQUES</bold>
            </p>
            <p> The article summarises the literature that points to the inadequacy of T&#x00fc;rkiye's Western image, despite the huge modernisation efforts in the Republican period. One criticism can be made of the article's approach to the 'top-down' nature of modernisation in the Republican period. It is clear that the modernisation movement in the Republican period was led by the Turkish elite, and in most cases it was a top-down social change. However, the article's constant emphasis on the notions of &#x2018;top-down&#x2019; and &#x2018;rapid modernisation&#x2019; inadvertently ignores the success of T&#x00fc;rkiye's transformation during the Republican period. Although most transformations during the Republican period were carried out with a top-down approach, most reforms were actually internalised by state institutions and society in the long run. There is not much room for negotiation on most of these reforms in T&#x00fc;rkiye today.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The article shows that the anti-EU stance in T&#x00fc;rkiye has not only been taken up by nationalists or Islamists, but also seriously by secular Kemalists and anti-capitalist politicians such as members of the Turkish Social Democrats (Bulent Ecevit's DSP party). The article gives several examples of how suspicious Kemalists and nationalists are of T&#x00fc;rkiye&#x2019;s EU bid. However, the article does not sufficiently explain the literature that shows why religious conservatives (or Islamists, according to some people) or mainly AK Party members had a very positive approach to T&#x00fc;rkiye-EU relations and successfully led probably the most vibrant period of T&#x00fc;rkiye-EU relations between 2002 and 2006. This point is crucial because those years had a huge impact on the development of the AK Party in the following years and shaped T&#x00fc;rkiye's last two decades.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Another missing point in the article is the view of European politicians on T&#x00fc;rkiye's European or non-European identity. Political history is shaped by various actors and institutions. Politicians play a major role in this shaping. There are several examples of the views and actions of Turkish politicians (e.g. &#x00d6;zal, Demirel and Ecevit) in the article. However, the views of European politicians were not sufficiently represented.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The article refers to Gummer (2010) and Vettes (1958) on page 4, while explaining the German and British perspectives in the relevant literature. In the rest of the paragraph, the authors underline the absence of the same topic in the French context. The authors can refer here to the works of Beyza C. Tekin. They already refer to her in the following pages, but this section also deserves a citation. The authors also refer to the Ottoman Orientalist approach on page 9. Edhem Eldem's work on this should be useful and deserves a mention here.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Finally, the issue of refugees has been one of the most important issues in T&#x00fc;rkiye-EU relations over the past decade. The article does not sufficiently discuss this issue and does not show the relevant literature that analyses T&#x00fc;rkiye-EU relations from the perspective of the refugee issue and its impact on identity discussions.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 
                <bold>CONCLUSION</bold>
            </p>
            <p> All in all, the article is right in its criticism that T&#x00fc;rkiye-EU relations are mostly studied in terms of how Europeans have represented T&#x00fc;rkiye rather than Turkish representations of Europe. This point is important. There is a widespread perception that Turks are already eager to join the EU, based on the views of both the public and the state. This interpretation is based on questionnaires only. Social reality is not always clearly reflected in quantitative data. It is easy to observe in T&#x00fc;rkiye that both state actors and the public are becoming more and more suspicious of the EU and its approach to T&#x00fc;rkiye every year.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In conclusion, this article is a great contribution and fills a gap in the field. I highly recommend its indexing.</p>
            <p> </p>
