            <p>This article presents an analytical overview of Turkish perceptions of Europe and European perceptions of Turkey, covering a broad historical period from the time of the French Revolution to the 21st century. I liked the study's approach to periodisation, as its division into four distinct chronological phases provides a well-organised and clear framework for analysis.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The article is a carefully crafted and well-organised analytical account that explores the representation of Self and Other within these two mutually constitutive entities. Overall, the article is an engaging and valuable scholarly contribution. Its significance extends to scholars specialising in the Self/Other nexus in International Relations, as well as to those concerned with understanding the dynamics of EU-Turkey relations. I believe it will be a reference for many of us interested in identity constructions and the politics of representation.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The study has a twofold aim: first, to identify Turkish conceptualisations and interpretations of Europe, including the evolution of images and representations over time. Second, and arguably more challenging, is to identify the main attributes and themes that characterise European representations of Turkey. This undertaking, which focuses on change and continuity over many centuries, presents a Herculean challenge. The authors skillfully provide an exhaustive and vivid account of Turkish perceptions of Europe and European perspectives on Turkey, traversing four key dimensions or 'focal issues': civilisation, status in international society, nationalism, and state-citizen relations.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In my view, the article succeeds in its first objective, which is to provide an insightful, analytical and more or less comprehensive review of studies on Turkish images and representations of Europe since the French Revolution. As for the second task, however, I believe that the sheer size of this vast, multilingual community makes it literally impossible to provide a comprehensive account of all scholarly work on Turkey's image in Europe. To address this, the authors tackle the problem by focusing their study on Turkish and English publications from two specific institutions: Sabanc&#x0131; and Ko&#x00e7; University Libraries.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The study's holistic approach potentially undermines the depth of its insights into the complexity of mutual images, representations and perceptions of Turkey in different parts of Europe. It is wonderful to see European images and representations of Turkey through three centuries in a single comprehensive analytical review, but this necessarily comes at the cost of losing valuable nuances. It would be useful if the authors could comment on how they deal with this potentially important loss of information due to the comprehensive scope of this long dur&#x00e9;e study.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The study could also benefit from a theoretical perspective at the beginning or end to explain how mutual representations are shaped and evolve over time. Can we speak of a collective imaginary/memory or habitus that has existed in this part of the world we call 'Europe' from the late eighteenth century to the present day? Can we really speak of &#x2018;the European&#x2019; representations of Turkey in the late eighteenth or early nineteenth century? Some European countries spent many centuries under Ottoman rule, others did not. Some sought a military alliance with the Ottoman Empire or Turkey against a common threat, others did not. So they are likely to have different memories and recollections, which are reflected in their images and representations of Turkey. Can we speak of similarities or divergent tendencies across the East-West or the South-North divide of the continent? These are some of the points that I think could be included in such a wonderful account of scholarship on the mutual representations of Europe and Turkey.</p>
