            <p> In my view, the project has several strong points: it is thorough, focuses on the (relative) longue duree in Turkish/European relations, and is multidisciplinary. This has allowed G&#x00fc;lmez, Topal and Rumelili to identify some important gaps in the literature, including, for instance, a lack of research on how Ottoman or early Republican reforms affected the Turkish image in Europe, or how European responses to Turkish immigration in the third period affected the European image in Turkey. The study has, importantly, also allowed the authors to identify certain key moments and themes in the development of the image of the Turk in Europe and of Europe in Turkey, and has allowed them to identify continuities and variations over time in this regard. In short, this is an important and valuable metastudy of the research on Turkish/European images and relations. A minor criticism is that there are several typos, spelling mistakes (e.g. visa-versa) and grammatical errors (especially regarding the use of articles. Therefore, while the language is generally clear and coherent, these relatively minor issues should be dealt with.&#x00a0;</p>
